# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ormond-butler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ormond-butler/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:ormond-butler/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] A native of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Pratt was a Civil War veteran and baseball player.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt was 5'7", 140 lbs., and compiled a 12–26 record in 43 professional games as a hurler.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] In successive years with Cleveland, 1871–1872, Pratt hit .262 and .277 in 45 games with a total of 52 hits.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt managed the Portsmouth, Ohio baseball team in 1868.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] Afterward he was a member of the Forest City Club of Cleveland in the Professional League of Baseball Players.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] This was the first professional league in America.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] In 1880 Pratt founded the first major league club in Pittsburgh, the Alleghenys (later renamed the Pittsburgh Pirates), which joined the American Association.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt celebrated his 90th birthday two days before his death in Pittsburgh on November 21, 1937.
[src:ormond-butler/al-pratt-baseball] He was buried, according to his request, attired in his Grand Army of the Republic uniform.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas attended Mississippi State University and signed with the Chicago White Sox in 1949.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] During his third season in the ChiSox' farm system, he was acquired by Cincinnati in 1951 and continued his minor league apprenticeship in the Reds' organization.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Loaned to the New York Yankees' Kansas City Blues affiliate in 1953 (Cincinnati at the time lacked a Triple-A farm team), Grammas collected a career-high 179 hits and batted .307.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] He was named the American Association's All-Star shortstop.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] With Roy McMillan blocking his path in Cincinnati, the Redlegs traded Grammas in December 1953 to the St.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Louis Cardinals; the trade marked an unusual "ping-pong" trend in Grammas' playing career, as he would bounce between Cincinnati (prior to 1954; 1956–58) and St.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] The Cardinals finally broke the pattern in June 1962 by trading Grammas to the Cubs, where he finished his career (1962–63).
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas was the Cardinals' starting shortstop in 1954, 1955 and 1959 and ranked no lower than third in fielding percentage among National League shortstops each season; he finished his career with a .969 overall fielding mark.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] He was a reserve infielder with the Redlegs and Cubs.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] All told, he appeared in 913 games played over ten MLB seasons, collecting 512 hits, with 90 doubles, ten triples, 12 home runs and 163 runs batted in.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] In 1964, Grammas began his managing career as skipper of the Cubs' Double-A affiliate, the Fort Worth Cats of the Texas League.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Although he spent the entire year at Fort Worth, as one of the Cubs' minor league pilots he was listed as a member of the Cubs' College of Coaches that season.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] He then joined Harry Walker's staff as the third base coach for the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1965, staying on following Walker's dismissal in mid-1967.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] He began his big-league managerial career when he was asked finish out the Pirates' 1969 season after Larry Shepard was fired as the team's manager on September 26.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Although Grammas guided the 1969 Bucs to a 4–1 finish, Danny Murtaugh took over as the team's manager in 1970.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas then returned to the Cincinnati Reds as third base coach under Sparky Anderson, spending six seasons in that post during the "Big Red Machine" era, including service on Cincinnati's 1970 and 1972 National League champions and the 1975 world champions.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] After the Milwaukee Brewers fired Del Crandall as manager near the end of the 1975 season, his place was taken on an interim basis by Harvey Kuenn.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] But following the 1975 World Series, the Brewers set their sights on Grammas as their next skipper, and signed him to a three-year contract in November 1975.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Milwaukee Brewers President Bud Selig said that Grammas was the only manager they wanted.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] He added, "There is no question in our mind, we got the best man available.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas was, however, unable to bring the success he had seen with the Reds to Milwaukee.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] In 1976 and 1977, Grammas led the Brewers to consecutive sixth-place finishes in the American League Eastern Division, in which the Brewers finished 32 and 33 games, respectively, out of first place.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Only the expansion 1977 Toronto Blue Jays, who lost 107 games in their inaugural season, kept the Brewers from consecutive last-place finishes under Grammas.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] A 10–5 start in 1976 led *Sports Illustrated* to publish a story praising Grammas' positive attitude and mental approach to the game.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] But the Brewers faded soon thereafter, losing 22 of their last 26 games.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Internal signs of trouble were evident by mid-season in 1977.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] With the Brewers at 39–45, Brewers reserve first baseman Mike Hegan, who was dissatisfied with his playing time under Grammas, made national news by saying "Grammas is a nice guy, but as a manager, he makes a good third base coach".
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Hegan added, "I think that we all expected that, when he came over here, he was going to provide motivation and leadership...but that hasn't happened".
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] After this point, the Brewers went 27–50.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] On November 21, 1977, Brewers President Bud Selig fired both Grammas and General Manager Jim Baumer.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas ended his managerial career with a record of 137–191.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas then returned to the coaching ranks and the Reds in 1978 as a member of Anderson's staff; then, after Anderson's controversial firing, Grammas coached under Bobby Cox with the 1979 Atlanta Braves.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] In mid-June of 1979, Anderson was hired as skipper of the Detroit Tigers, and during his first off-season as Detroit's manager, he added Grammas to his staff as third base coach, where Grammas served for 12 consecutive years (1980–91), including on the Tigers' 1984 world championship season.
[src:ormond-butler/alex-grammas] Grammas died at his home in Birmingham, Alabama on September 13, 2019.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:ormond-butler/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:ormond-butler/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] In 1917, Burwell was drafted into the United States Army.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] During the Battle of Saint-Mihiel in 1918, Burwell volunteered for the dangerous mission of attacking German machine gun nests, and his pitching hand was injured by a bullet.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] One of his fingers was shattered and the tip of the finger was lost, causing his fingers to have a slight curl.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He'd discover after his hand healed that he could throw a sinker.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He pitched for all or parts of 12 straight seasons, between 1923 and 1934, for the Indianapolis Indians of the American Association.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] In Major League Baseball, he appeared in 66 career games for the 1920–21 St.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Louis Browns and four contests for the 1928 Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] In his 70 MLB games, six as a starting pitcher, he won nine games and lost eight, with a 4.37 earned run average.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He posted six saves and one complete game, allowing 253 hits and 79 bases on balls, with 49 strikeouts, in 2181⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He also fashioned a lengthy post-pitching career as a minor league manager (including two seasons, 1945–46, as skipper of the Indianapolis franchise) and Major League coach.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He worked in the latter role for the Boston Red Sox (1944) and Pittsburgh Pirates (1947–48; 1958–62).
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] While serving as pitching coach on Danny Murtaugh's staff, Burwell was a member of the Pirates' 1960 world championship team.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Burwell was acting manager of the Pirates for the final game of the 1947 season, after player-manager Billy Herman resigned with one game remaining.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Under Burwell, the Pirates defeated the Cincinnati Reds, 7–0.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] He also was a longtime scout and roving minor league coach for the Pirates.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] While working as pitching instructor in the Pirate organization in 1949, Burwell was instrumental to the development of pitcher Vern Law, then toiling for the Class B Davenport Pirates of the Illinois–Indiana–Iowa League.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Burwell taught the 19-year-old Law how to change speeds and throw the change-up.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Law — winner of the 1960 Cy Young Award as the top pitcher in the majors — later cited Burwell as the coach who most helped him during his time in the minor leagues.
[src:ormond-butler/bill-burwell] Burwell died at age 78 in Ormond Beach, Florida, and is buried in nearby Daytona Beach.
[src:ormond-butler/ormond-butler] Butler was born in West Virginia, and died at age 60 in Mount Hope, Maryland.
